Figure Caption: XRD patterns for AlxCoCrFeNi alloys. (a) All alloys, and (b) main peak in single-phase alloys, i.e. (111) for FCC and (110) for BCC, are shown. The shaded area in H-0 in (b) indicates how the relative intensity in the XRD peaks is calculated.
Diagrams for (a) electrical resistivity at temperatures in 300–400K, (b) electrical resistivity at temperatures in 4–400K, and (c) electrical conductivity vs.xin AlxCoCrFeNi alloys.
Diagrams for curves of thermal conductivity as a function of temperature (a), and as a function ofxin AlxCoCrFeNi alloys (b), respectively.
Lorenz numbers for AlxCoCrFeNi alloys vs. temperature.

Variation of thermal expansion coefficient with temperature of AlxCoCrFeNi alloys. The maximum and minimum values are shown at the upper left-hand side of each curve, and the Curie temperature is shown in the gray region. Note that there is another “valley” for H-0.875 and H-1 in the figure. The interval in CTE coordinate is 15×10−6K−1.

(a) DTA curves of AlxCoCrFeNi alloys forx=0.75, 0.875, and 1. (b) HTXRD patterns for Al0.875CoCrFeNi alloy at temperatures from 773K to 973K, showing the presence of another phase, σ=NiCoCr, except α and γ solid solution phases at temperature 923K and 973K, and indicating precipitation of σ at temperature equal to or higher than 873K.
Monotonic decrease in coefficient of thermal-expansion (CTE in 10−6K−1) vs.xin AlxCoCrFeNi alloys. Note that slope of CTE in FCC structure is higher than that of in BCC structure.
Curve for Curie temperature and molecular field vs.xin AlxCoCrFeNi alloys. The results are obtained from analysis of CTE and XRD data.
